    "source_sections": {
      "references": "[Gu04] Guy, Richard K., Unsolved problems in number theory. (2004), xviii+437.",
      "remarks": "A problem of Finucane. One can also ask similar questions about $n\\mapsto \\sigma(n)-1$: do iterates of this always reach a prime? If so, how soon? (It is easily seen that iterates of this cannot reach the same prime infinitely often, since they are non-decreasing.)\n\nThis problem is somewhat ambiguously phrased. Let $F(n)$ count the number of iterations of $n\\mapsto \\phi(n)+1$ before reaching a prime. The number of iterations required is A039651 in the OEIS.\n\nCambie notes in the comments that $F(n)=o(n)$ is trivial, and $F(n)=1$ infinitely often. Presumably the intended question is to find 'good' upper bounds for $F(n)$.\n\nThis is discussed in problem B41 of Guy's collection \\cite{Gu04}."
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "number theory",
      "iterated functions"
    ]
  },
